{
  "texts": [
    "The latter expresses the simple withdrawal of i 0 from the initial p-structure without any other change.",
    "At the level of the p-foundation the simple withdrawal of agent i 0 from the p-site is expressed by a new profile that attributes the empty set as aspirations to the withdraw party, while the aspirations of other parties are kept unchanged.",
    "This motivates the following: Definition A.2.1 For any p-site a = ( (I, A, (A i))), the p-site that results from withdrawal of i 0 is a -i 0 ∶= ( (I, A, (B i))) where B i 0 ∶= ∅, B i ∶= A i (i ∈ I ∖ {i 0 }).",
    "▽Note that in general, within the p-site δ i 0 j 0 a = ( (I, A, (B i))), image of a by δ i 0 j 0 (Definition and notation 3.1.5), agent i 0 is silenced (B i 0 = ∅) but his/her aspirations are delegated to j 0 (B j 0 = A i 0 ∪ A j 0).",
    "The following lemma details what is implied by a delegation that results in the withdrawal of the delegating agent.Lemma A.2.2 Let δ i 0 j 0 ∶ I → I be a delegation function and let a ≡ ( (I, A, (A i))) ∈ PSITE(I, A)."
  ]
}